### Short summary
- R can be seen as both a _programming language_ and a _statistics package_
- A very useful IDE for R development is _RStudio_
- Building up a basic vocabulary enables you to quickly learn more about R programming
- The duality of R makes it an ideal meeting spot for statisticians, programmers, and analysts



---

## R - a statistics package
R is a _statistics package_ much like SPSS, SAS or Stata.

Being open source, R enables quick development of new functionality.

There are literally thousands of open source libraries ("packages") for R for just about any statistics task there is.

R is _code driven_ - there are graphical frontends for R as well but the area where R really shines is in its well-structured syntax.

---

## R - a programming language
R is a feature complete _programming language_ similar to Python, Ruby or JavaScript.

Being open source with a fairly easy syntax, programmers can quickly get up to speed with application development in R.

R _is not for everyone_ but can be used for speedy and flexible development of a wide range of applications.


---

### Typical use cases
Since R is both for statistical programming and other kinds of development, R can be very practical in situations where the two meet, e.g.:
- Automated report building
- Data visualization and analysis
- Data-driven web applications
- Database middle-end/front-end development

--- 

## RStudio

RStudio is a powerful Integrated Development Environment (IDE) for R

Features include syntax highlighting; audit and debug functionality; integration with tools for packaging code and generating documentation; and visualization tools; etc.


